<PB N="309" REF="356">with the re&s;t of the realm; on which the bi&s;hop i&s;&s;ued his commi&s;&s;ions for levying the &s;ame, as well in Durham and Sadberge, as Norham: The king thought &s;it in his wi&s;dom to i&s;&s;ue his letters patent for the indemnity of the bi&s;hop and his people, that the &s;ame might not become a prejudicial precedent for future times. It is ob&s;ervable, that the &s;ame language, in the preamble of the royal writ, is u&s;ed, as in that of the bi&s;hop of Durham, noted in the year 1348: <HI>Sciatis quod cum mag|nates proceres &amp; tota communitas regni no&s;tri Anglioe,</HI> &amp;c. In 1377 the king granted an inhibition again&s;t the archbi&s;hop of York's vi&s;itations and extortions within the See of Durham; and in the &s;ame year the bi&s;hop granted a toll on certain merchandi&s;e brought to Durham to defray the charges of paving and repairing the walls of the city<NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">In the year 1355 the bi&s;hop, under his privy &s;eal, appointed a fore&s;ter for Che&s;ter. <HI>Rot. A. Hatfield,</HI> N&deg; 5, <HI>indor&s;o.</HI>&mdash;Randal's MSS.
<P>In 1366 he granted, to John de Ogle and others, free warren in Hardwick, Sheraton, and Ne&s;bit. <HI>Rot. A. Hatfield, Sch.</HI> 14, N&deg; 4.&mdash;Ibid.</P>
<P>In 1370 a commi&s;&s;ion i&s;&s;ued to enquire after certain lands appropriated to the repair of Shincliff bridge. <HI>Rot. A. Hatfield, Sch.</HI> 1. N&deg; 4, <HI>indor&s;o.</HI>&mdash;Ibid.</P>
<P>In 1372 a commi&s;&s;ion i&s;&s;ued to enquire after the wages of labourers, and put in force the &s;tatute. <HI>Rot. B. Hatfield. Sch.</HI> 7, N&deg; 1.&mdash;Ibid.</P>
<P>And in the &s;ame year we find a record of the bi&s;hop's, wrote to liberate a clerk, who was acquitted of a charge of murder. <HI>Rot. B. Hatfield, Sch.</HI> 9. N&deg; 2.&mdash;Ibid.</P>
<P>In 1373 the bi&s;hop granted land in Auckland for an hermitage. <HI>Rot. B. Sch.</HI> 9. <HI>indor&s;o.</HI>&mdash; Ibid.</P>
<P>And that year we have the record of a return to an enquiry touching aliens that enjoyed eccletia&s;tical bene|&s;ices within the See, to the following effect.</P>
<P>11 <HI>th Dec.</HI> 1377, <HI>Fox's Martyrs, vol.</HI> 1, <HI>p.</HI> 489. <HI>Reg. Hatfield, p.</HI> 129.</P>
<P>Jacob de Ur&s;inis, cardinal of Rome, was in po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of the archdeaconry of Durham, value 200 marl$s, Dominus Roger de Ripon held, <HI>fructus tanquam firmarius &s;eu con&s;titutus cuju&s;dem,</HI> of Peter Ru&s;pii of Lon|bardy, procurator, <HI>&s;eu firmarii principa is candinalis &s;upra dicti.</HI></P>
<P>Ma&s;ter cardinal Gibbon is in po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of the pari&s;h church of Weremouth, value 200 marks.</P>
<P>The mona&s;tery of S. Sixtus, in the city of Rome, have in the church of Bambrough, Northumberland, 2$ <ABBR>l.</ABBR> 6 <ABBR>s.</ABBR> 8 <ABBR>d.</ABBR> payable by the prior and convent of St Ofwald, of No&s;tel, in the dioce&s;e of York. Dated at Hoveden, 16th Jan. 1377, 33 <ABBR>d</ABBR> of the con&s;ecration.</P>
<P><HI>Conce&s;&s;io pro pavimento et muragio civitatis Dunelm. Rot. B. Hatfield, Sch.</HI> 2, N&deg; 4.</P>
<P>Tho. Dei gra. ep. D. Burgen&s;ibus et al. probis ho'ib's in civitate n'ra Dun. &amp;c. Nov'it is nos. vob. in anxilium civitat. n're p'd'ce claude'de et pavime'tu' in ead. rep'and et &s;aciend. &amp;c. capiatis de rebus venalib's a$cand. civitat. veniend. videl't de quol't &s;umagio bladi aut bra&s;ei venali cuju&s;cu'q' generis &s;it unu' obulu' a$enti. de quol't doleo vini, &amp;c. de quol't &s;acco lane. &amp;c. de quol't equo equa bove et vacca, &amp;c. de quol't $$reo equi, equae, bovis et vaccae fri&s;to aut &s;alito aut tan'ato', &amp;c. de qual't la&s;ta corcor, &amp;c. de quinque $$conibus, &amp;c. de decem ovibus et capris, &amp;c. de quinque porcis, &amp;c. de dece' velleribus, &amp;c. de qual't cen|$ea$ pell$u' lanitar. &amp;c. de qual't centena pelliu' agnor. cuniculor. vulpiu'leporu' lator. et &s;quirrellor, &amp;c. de qual't centena gri&s;i operis, &amp;c. de quol't quarl'io &s;alis, &amp;c. de quol't panno integro, &amp;c. de qual't centena $$$aorum de wor&s;ted, &amp;c. de quol't tapeto de wor&s;ted, qui vocat coverlit, &amp;c. de qual't centena $ele $$uce et canevas, &amp;c. de quol't chies de &s;indone a&s;&s;orciat. &amp;c. de qual't centena Millewelli &s;aliti aut duri pi&s;cis marini, &amp;c. de quol't &s;almone, &amp;c. de quol't &s;um'agio &s;almon, &amp;c. de quol't milliar. alec. &amp;c. de quol't &s;um'agio cineru', &amp;c. de quol't &s;um'agio de wadd, &amp;c. de duob's milliar. allior. aut ceparu', &amp;c. qual't duodena de cordwayn, &amp;c. de qual't duodena de ra&s;an, &amp;c. de quol't pari molaru' aut rotar. &amp;c. de quol't &s;um'agio plumbi, ferri, aut &s;tagni, &amp;c. de qual't petra uncti &s;epi butiri et ca&s;$i, &amp;c. de qual't carectata bru&s;&s;i aut bruere, &amp;c. de qual't carectata cami&s;i, &amp;c. de qual't centena cere, &amp;c. de qual't cente|na pi'pis, &amp;c. de qual't centena amigdol. &amp;c. de qual't centena cumini, &amp;c. de qual't centena de madyr. &amp;c. de quol't milliar. cardonu', &amp;c. de quol't &s;um'agio cu' batry, &amp;c. de qual't caractata de batry &s;p'iali, poltry et aliis m'cimoniis, &amp;c. de quol't carectata fructuu', &amp;c. de quol't &s;um'agio &s;ructuu', &amp;c. de quol't &s;um'agio m'ciu', &amp;c. de quol't tru&s;&s;ello cuju&s;cu'q' m'cis venal. exceden. vigil'l &s;. in valores, &amp;c. 6th Mar. 1377.&mdash;Rudd's and Randal's MSS.</P>
<P>This record is &s;o far curious, as that it &s;hews all &s;pecies of merchandi&s;e then expo&s;ed to &s;ale at Durham.</P>
<P>He nominated, this year, a$keeper of the park of Wol&s;ingham. <HI>Rot. B. Hatfield, Sch.</HI> 6, N&deg; 3, <HI>indor&s;o.</HI>&mdash; Ibid.&mdash;And he i&s;&s;ued a commi&s;&s;ion to enquire of the tre&s;pa&s;&s;es committed at Stainton.</P></NOTE>. In 1378, by letters patent, he appointed Wm de Elmedon
<PB N="310" REF="357">gaoler and porter of the ca&s;tle of Durham, with certain profits annexed to that office, among which are fees for &s;ealing the mea&s;ures to be u&s;ed in the city of Dur|ham<NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot"><HI>Carta Will'i de Elmeden de offic. gaolator et janitoris Ca&s;tri Dunelm. Rot. B. Hatfield, Sch.</HI> 4, N&deg; 4.
<P>Tho. D. g. &amp;c. Sciatis q'd p' bono g'tuito, &amp;c. Will's de Elmeden, &amp;c. dedimus et co'ce&s;&s;imus p' nob. et &s;uce. n'r's epi&s;. Dun. q'ntu' in nob. e&s;t eid. Will'o officia gaolator et janitor ca&s;tri Dun. n'rs h'end et te|nend. cid. W'o et a&s;&s;ign. &s;uis ad tota' vita' ip'ius p'cipiendo in offic. illis feoda et vadia &s;ub&s;cripta videl't quol't anno de nob. et &s;ucc. n'ris una' robab et e&s;cam. p' &s;ervicio quol't die ad men&s;a co'&s;tabulariis p'd'ci ca&s;tri, et p' &s;'viente &s;uo cu&s;todiente p'tam d'ci ca&s;tri e&s;cam, cu' garconibus d'ci co'&s;tabularij p'cipiendo etia' proficia &s;ingula de motis cirea ca&s;tru' p'd'c'm, necno' p' qual't men&s;urar. &s;ub&s;cripturu' videl't bu&s;&s;el, dimid. bu&s;&s;ell, peck, lagena potell, et quarta cu' co'tigerit illas &s;igillari, unu' den'ium. Co'ce&s;&s;imus etiam eid. Will'o q'd ip'e p'cipiat de parco n'ro vocato le' bi&s;hop meadowe fenum &s;ufficiens ad unn' equu' p' cu&s;todia eju&s;d. parei. Co'ce&s;&s;imus etia' eid. p'd'co W'o q'd ip'e he'at totu. fimum <HI>(fumage, manure or dung)</HI> infra i'd ca&s;tru', et quibu&s;l't duodecim. &s;eptimanis unu' quarteriu' fr'i <HI>(frumenti)</HI> et quol't a&deg; quinq' &s;. p. &s;'viente &s;uo compediente et de compediente pri&s;ones, et q'tuor &s;. p. d'co &s;'viente &s;uo cu&s;todiente p'tam ca&s;tri p'd'ci, &amp;c. In cujus, &amp;c. pat. &amp;c. 8th Oct. 1378.&mdash;Randal's MSS.</P></NOTE> He granted, this year, to Ralph lord Neville, a market and fair at Stain|drop<NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot">Spearman's Enq. p. 19. Rot. B. Hatfield, Sch. 5, N&deg; 1.
<P>For this licence, &s;ee Raby, vol. ii. of this work.</P>
<P>Rot. B. Hatfield, Sch. 4, N&deg; 8. For this grant, &s;ee Staindrop, vol. ii.</P>
<P>Sched. 5, N&deg; 2, indor&s;o. See Staindrop, vol. ii.</P></NOTE>. In 1379 there appears to be an officer in appointment, not mentioned in any preceding record, a trea&s;urer of the hou&s;ehold. In 1380 is a record of commi&s;&s;ion to ju&s;tices of a&s;&s;ize<NOTE N="&Dagger;" PLACE="foot">Rot. B. Hatfield, Sch. 8, N&deg; 1.</NOTE>; a commi&s;&s;ion empowering the convent to exchange, with Bela|&s;is, Henknoll, near Auckland, for lands in Wolvi&s;ton<NOTE N="&Verbar;" PLACE="foot">Rot. B. Hatfield, Sch. 2, N&deg; 3. For this account, &s;ee St Andrew, Auckland, vol. ii. of this work.</NOTE>; a power to purcha&s;e lands for the endowment of Durham college in Oxford<NOTE N="&sect;" PLACE="foot">Rot. B. Hatfield, Sch. 2, indor&s;o.
<P>Tho. &amp;c. Conce&s;&s;imus licentiam, &amp;c. adquirere, &amp;c. h'end, et tenend. &s;ibi et &s;ucc. &s;uis in pura. et p'pe|petna, ele$mo&s;inam ad manutenend. et &s;u&s;tenand. octo mo'achos capell$s et octo paup'es &s;cholares in colle|gio n'ro Dun. apud Oxon. p' nos de novo &s;undato, &amp;c.&mdash;Randal's MSS. Vide Smith's Annals of Univ. Coll, p. 375.</P></NOTE>; an in&s;titution of chaplains to do duty in the new manor-hou&s;e at London<NOTE N="&para;" PLACE="foot">Rot. B. Hatfield, Sch. 8, N&deg; 4.</NOTE>; and a protection granted by let|ters patent to John de Bille&s;ton vicar of Norton, but for what cau&s;e is not &s;peci|fied<NOTE N="**" PLACE="foot">Tho. &amp;c. Sciatis q'd &s;u&s;cepimus in p'tectionem et defen&s;ionem n'ram dil'cu' cler. n'rum Joh'em de Bille&s;ton vic'num eccl'ie de Norton qui nobi&s;cu' in ho&s;picio n'ro p' preceptu' n'rum moratur ho'es terras res redditus et oc's po&s;&s;e&s;&s;iones &s;uas et ideo volds mandamus q'd ip'u Joh'em ho'es tenas res redditus o'es po&s;|&s;$&s;&s;iones &s;uas manuteneatis p'tegatis, &amp;c. Rot. B. Hatfield, Sch. 3, indor&s;o.&mdash;Randal's MSS.</NOTE>. In regard to royal fi&s;h, Spearman &s;ays<NOTE N="&dagger;&dagger;" PLACE="foot">P. 20.</NOTE>, in this prelate's time,
<PB N="311" REF="358">(37 Edw. III. 1363) John de Carow having through ignorance &s;eized a royal fi&s;h ca&s;t upon his lands there, and being que&s;tioned for it by his charter or deed, ac|knowledged his tre&s;pa&s;s, and that it belonged to the bi&s;hop, in right of his church of Durham, and agreed for 100 marks damage<NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">Rot. A. Sch. 16, N&deg; 1. For this deed, &s;ee Sea$on, C. vol ii. of this work.</NOTE>. This author al&s;o &s;ays, <Q>The bi|&s;hops &startq;of Durham likewi&s;e re&s;erved and enjoyed the cu&s;toms and profits of &s;hips and fi&s;h within the ports of the county palatine, and anchorage, beaconage, and &endq;other &s;uch like pro&s;its and duties accruing thereby<NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot">Regi&s;tro. 2. Decani et. capituli Dunelm. 164. &s;&s;. Hugo epi&s;. Dunelm. anno Hen. II. regis 1154, per chartam &s;uam d' Burgo d' Weremne (al's Wearmouth) fecit provi&s;ionem pro navibus ibidem negociant. refervando cu&s;tumas pi&s;cium.
<P>Compotum auditor epi&s;c. et cancellar, ejus de redditibus burgi et. pa&s;&s;agii trans rivum per ferry-boat ibi|dem, pi&s;ear. ibidem et pro applicatione navium ibidem ac pro batellis et cymbis, annis 1 Hen. II. 19 Edw. III. 7 Hen. IV. 5 Hen. V. 36 Hen VI. et 17, 18, 24 Hen. VII. regis.&mdash;p. 23 et 24.</P></NOTE>.</Q></P>
<P>Befides the beneficent works before mentioned, bi&s;hop Hatfield gave to the convent, at his death, the &s;tock which he had in Weredale, e&s;timated at 400 marks and upwards; his jewels and in&s;ignia, together with 300 marks in &s;ilver; a red ve&s;tment embroidered with figures in gold, be&s;ides many &s;ilver ve&s;&s;els and valuable ornaments: One article Chambr&egrave; notes, among the things given to the convent, was, a thorn of the crown Chri&s;t wore during his pa&s;&s;ion, which the bi&s;hop had received as a precious relic by the gift of Edw. III. After a tedious illne&s;s, the bi&s;hop departed this life on the 8th day of May, 1381, at his manor of Aleford near London, in the 36th year of his epi&s;copacy, and was buried with great fune|ral pomp, according to the directions in his will, in the tomb he had prepared for him&s;elf in the cathedral church of Durham, whereon is his effigy, and many coats of arms, but no in&s;cription<NOTE N="&Dagger;" PLACE="foot">In the herald's office, among Dugdale's MSS. notat. c. 41, there is a beautiful drawing of this tomb, and al&s;o an engraving thereof in the Antiquarian Repertory. Many authors have mi&s;takenly adopted arms for this bi&s;hop which never were borne by him or any of the name, but have been painted upon his monu|ment by &s;ome novice of a workman; for thereon it appears, that the chevron is cut in relief upon the &s;hield, but the lions are not, and that the arms of the Black Prince appear on the &s;ame monument cut in relief on the &s;hield, and the painter has painted over the whole, in order to deface it, and probably to plea&s;e his own fancy, with the chevron, and three lions rampant argent. This circum&s;tance puts it o$t of all manner of doubt, that the arms on the monument are mo&s;t of them (if not every one) fal&s;e.&mdash;See Antiquarian Re|pertory, vol. iv. p. 119.</NOTE>. A di&s;pute aro&s;e re&s;pecting the ceremonies of his fu|neral, the circum&s;tances of which are now little intere&s;ting<NOTE N="&sect;" PLACE="foot">The Sec vacant. John de Marton oc. temporal chancellor, 9th May, 1345.
