<P>Randal's MSS.</P></NOTE>: He expended the &s;um of 499 <ABBR><HI>l.</HI></ABBR> 6 <ABBR><HI>s.</HI></ABBR> 7 <ABBR><HI>d.</HI></ABBR> in the reparation of the gallile; where he founded, or rather enlarged, the endowment of a chantry, called, in the old writers, a marble chantry, for two prie&s;ts to celebrate daily ma&s;s there<NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot">W. de Chambre.&mdash;Ang. S$c. 776.</NOTE>. He founded two &s;chools upon the Green Place in Durham, the one for grammar learning, the other for mu&s;ic. The &s;um of 838 <ABBR><HI>l.</HI></ABBR> was expended in building the cloi&s;ter to the priory at Durham, towards which the cardinal gave 238 <ABBR><HI>l.</HI></ABBR> 17 <ABBR><HI>s.</HI></ABBR>. He erected the whole of the pre&s;ent gaol, with the gateway thereto, where an ancient gate &s;tood, gone to decay. Before this edifice was made, criminals and other
<PB N="333" REF="380">pri&s;oners were confined in cells and vaults in the towers of the ca&s;tle. He made great improvements at the manor of Hoveden, and built the we&s;tern gates to the cemetary-yard, with a beautiful lodge adjoining, where his arms are placed. He recovered by &s;uit in the king's court, again&s;t the mayor and commonalty of the town of Newca&s;tle upon Tyne, the third part of Tyne-bridge on the &s;outh end, with the tower built there by the mayor of that place, together with all privileges thereto appertaining<NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">Wm de Chambre. Angl. Sac. p. 776.
<P>"Sey&s;enne and po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion was taken for the &s;aid Bi&s;hopp's u&s;e by virtue of a warrant of atturnie from the Bi&s;hoppe, by Sir Raphe Urie, knight, and other two joyned with him, a&s;&s;i&s;ted by many knights, e&s;quires, and others, &s;ome of who&s;e names are &s;ub&s;cribed, vixt. Knights of the Bi&s;hopricke,&mdash;John Lumley, Raphe Eurie, Robert Hilton, William Fulthroppe, William Tempe&s;t, Thomas Suerties, Robert Conyers, William Claxton, then &s;heriffe of the countie, John Cowycke, William Lumley, Thomas Lambert, William Eurie. Knights of the county of Northumberland,&mdash;Robert Ogle, John Bartram, John Widdrington, and John Middleton. Knights of We&s;tmerland,&mdash;Chri&s;topher Mori&s;by, William O&s;andlaw. E&s;quires,&mdash;Robert Curie, William Bowes, John Conyers, William Lampton the elder, William Lampton the younger, Hugh Burninghill, John Mordon, William Billingham, John Bellys, Henry Tailboys, Thomas Garboys, John Hutton, William Kimton, Thomas Cooke of Pi&s;hburne, with other &s;ive e&s;quires."</P>
<P>Hall's MSS. in the D. and Ch. Library, Durham.</P></NOTE>. He obtained a di&s;pen&s;ation from the pope for erecting a bapti&s;mal font in the gallile of the church at Durham, where the children of per|&s;ons excommunicated might receive the offices of the church, from which, other|wi&s;e, they were prohibited<NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot">Ang. Sac. 776.</NOTE>. He was a benefactor to the bridge at Roche&s;ter<NOTE N="&Dagger;" PLACE="foot">Lel. Itin. v. 6.</NOTE>. In 1425 he granted an indulgence to all per&s;ons who &s;hould contribute to build|ing a new &s;tone bridge over the river Eamot, in the pari&s;h of Penrith, Cumberland. In 1410 he granted a like indulgence of forty days to all &s;uch as &s;hould contribute to the redemption of Simon Chandy, a burge&s;s of Newca&s;tle, and captive in war<NOTE N="&sect;" PLACE="foot">Regi&s;ter. Langley 31 &mdash;Univer&s;is X'ti fidelibus prae&s;entes I'ras in&s;pecturis Thomas, &amp;c. &s;al. cupien|$es p. allectiva indulgentiarum munera mentes fidelium ad caritativae devotionis opera quantum cum Deo po&s;&s;imus propen&s;uis excitare, Dei omnipotentes mi&s;ericordia beati&s;&s;imaeq. virginis Mariae matris &s;uae ac be$|torum Petri et Pauli apo&s;tolorum ejus, nec non &s;ancti&s;&s;imi confe&s;&s;ores Cuthberti patroni n'ri omniun$$. &s;anctorum meritis et precibus confidentes omnibus et &s;ingulis parochianis n'ris et aliis quorum dioce&s;ani ha$$ n'ram indulgentiam ratam habuerint, de peceatis &s;uis vere contritis, penitentibus et confe&s;&s;is ad redemp|tionem Simonis Chandy de villa Novi Ca&s;tri et n'rae dioces, qui nuper per inimicos n'ros Franciae erat cap|tus, ac ibidem carceribus mancipatus quorum manus evadere non poterat priu&s;quam &s;e obligaverat dic$is ini|micis &s;olvere pro ip&s;ius liberatione magnam pecuniae &s;ummam, quam &s;ine &s;idelium elemo&s;inis et auxiliis ip&s;i|tolvere non valebit, grata de bonis a Deo &s;ibi collatis contulerint &s;ub&s;idia caritatis 40 dies indulgentia$ con|cedimus per pre&s;entes p. annu. tantummodo duraturas. Datas London in ho&s;pitio no&s;tro die 8&deg; men&s;$. Martij A. D. 1410.&mdash; Randal's MSS.</NOTE>. He granted licence to Ralph earl of We&s;tmorland to empark forty acres of his lands at Whitworth, and all the lands late of Richard del Park, in Biers, which he had acquired, ea&s;t of the road leading from Binche&s;ter to Willington, together with his woods of Whitworth and Tudhoe<NOTE N="&Verbar;" PLACE="foot">Rot. B. Langley, N^o 54. Vide Whitworth, vol. ii.</NOTE>. He disfore&s;ted certain lands at Che&s;ter, and licen&s;ed their being enclo&s;ed and brought into tillage<NOTE N="&para;" PLACE="foot">E. copyhold book, marked C. on the back, p. 530.&mdash;Ryton, 1413.&mdash;Halm. de Che&s;tre, 3&deg; die Mai$, $$o pont. Thome 7&deg;.&mdash;Randal's MSS.</NOTE>. Among the patent officers appointed by him are, a receiver-general, a clerk of the works, a &s;urveyor-general, and a keeper of Franklin Park<NOTE N="**" PLACE="foot">Ree. gen. and clerk of the works. Langley Rot. E.&mdash;Surveyor-gen. Langley Rot. A. N^o 10.&mdash; Keeper of Franklyn Park. Langley Rot. C. N^o 67.
<P>A. D. 1409 licence was granted to Ra. Neville, Earl of We&s;tmoreland, to found a college at Stain|drop. Vide Staindrop, vol. ii. E. mon. Ang. tom. iii. p. 11, 142.</P>
<P>A. D. 1410 he granted a licence to Sir Ra. Eure, to fortify his ca&s;tle of Witton with a wall, and to em|battle, encarnale, entower, and fortify the &s;ame. Rot. A. Langley, N^o 22. Vide Witton, vol. ii.</P>
<P>A. D. 1422 the like to fortify Ludworth. Rot. E. Langley, indor&s;o N^o. 50. Vide Ludworth, vol ii.</P>
<P>A. D. 1431 the like to fortify Bradley-hall. Vide Bradley, vol. ii.</P></NOTE>.</P>
<PB N="334" REF="381">
<P>The plague raged in the city of Durham and its environs to that terrible de|gree, during the cardinal's time, that in 1416 he i&s;&s;ued his proclamation to ad|journ the great &s;e&s;&s;ions. This vi&s;itation continued to carry off a multitude of people for five years<NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">N^o. 18. Rot. Langley B. in Cancel. Dun &mdash;Thomas, d. g. &amp;c. vicecomiti Dunelm. &s;al. Quia tam propter gravem pe&s;tilentiam quae in civitate no&s;tra Dunelm. et partibus vicinis, adiu e&s;t duravit et adhuc quod dolendum e&s;t durat, quam quibu&s;dam aliis de cau&s;is nos moventibus, omnes a&s;&s;i&s;as iuratas certificationes et attinctas coram ju&s;ticiariis no&s;tris apud Dunelm. in comitat. Dunelm. arraiand. quae coram eis die Jo|vis proximo ante fe&s;tum S. Matthei apo&s;toli re&s;tant capiend. ac omnia alia brevia placita coronae et querelas coram eis pendentia u&s;q. ad diem Lunae proximum po&s;t fe&s;tum circumci&s;ionis d'ni duximus proroganda et adjornanda. Et ideo tibi praecipimus quod omnia brevia no&s;tra originalia et judicialia coram praefatis ju&s;ti|ciariis n'ris ad dictum diem Jovis retornabilia coram praefatis ju&s;ticiariis ad dictum diem Lunae in forma debita retornari facias. Dat. 15&deg; die Sept. a'o pontif. n'ri 12&deg; 1416.&mdash; Randal's MSS.
<P>Commi&s;&s;ions were i&s;&s;ued, for arraying &s;oldiers and equipping &s;hips, by this prelate &s;even times in different years, viz. annis 3, 9, 12, 24, 29, 30, et 31. pont. &s;ui. Rot. A. 26. dor&s;o. Rot. 1. N^o 1. Rot. B.</P>
<P>Spearman's Enq. p. 12.</P>
<P>Com'i&s;&s;io e'pi ad inquirend. et re&s;tituend. mercimonia capta cum nave tanquam bona inimicor. p. cer tas p'&s;onas Novi Ca&s;tri et quae ad manus horum infra com. pal. deveni&s;&s;ent. Sup. l'ras &s;ub c'o'i &s;igillo villae de Bruges certifican. q'd fuerunt bona burgen&s;ium d'cae villae de Bruges.&mdash;V. indulgentias p. d'c'm ep'm conce&s;&s;. o'ib's qui eleemo&s;yn. et pecunias darent pro reparac'one Lame&s;ley-brig ultra aquam de Tame 1426, Rog'ro e'pi fo. 180;&mdash;reparatione pontis de Corbrig ultra aquam de Tyne ib'm fo. 137;&mdash;Hayden-brig ul|tra Tyne fo. 147;&mdash;pro pontis ultra Tyne juxta vill. Novi Ca&s;tri ib'm fo. 160, et p. ponte faciendo inter Halghton et Burdon 1430 fo. 176.</P>
<P>Bre. e'pi de p'clamac'one faciend. q'd o'i'es ho'nes parati &s;int ad p'fici&s;eend. et defended. ver&s;us Scotes.</P>
<P>B'p Langley, by his writ to the &s;heriff of Durham <HI>"Ad intendend. Johanni comiti Huntingdon admirallo regis ver&s;us Boream, vel ejus deputat per commi&s;&s;ionem &s;uam con&s;titu. in arre&s;tando naves pro &s;ervitio domini regis, vel faciend. alia officium admirallitatis tangentia &s;ecus litus maris infra regiam libertatem epi&s;c. Dunelm. rega|libus libertatibus no&s;tris et con&s;uetudinibus eccle&s;. n'rae Dunelm. d' antiquo tempore u&s;itat. in omnibus &s;emper &s;al|vis."</HI> Rot. D. N^o 3. 15 K. H. VI. 1437.&mdash;Ibid. Enq. p. 13.</P>
<P>B'p Langley granted an aid to the town of Hartlepool in the time of K. Hen. IV. Rot. B. N^o 15. dor&s;o.&mdash;Ibid. Enq. p. 16.</P>
<P>He granted a commi&s;&s;ion in the time of K. Hen. IV. or V. to enquire touching the collection of a &s;ub&s;idy for the king. Rot. C. N^o 30.&mdash;Ibid. Enq. p. 16.</P>
<P><HI>Thomae Langley, epi&s;c. conce&s;&s;io mercat. de Stanhope. Per chart. H. Pud&s;ey epi&s;c. temp. K. Hen. II.</HI> 1143, Rot E. N^o 7&deg;.&mdash;Ibid. Enq. p. 18.</P>
<P>In the times of K. Hen. IV. and V. he granted commi&s;&s;ions <HI>"Roberto Jack&s;on, coronatori &s;uo in warda d' Ea&s;ington,</HI> and inqui&s;itions were taken thereon <HI>d' bonis et merchandizis per naufragium infra regiam liberta|tem Dunel. viz. infra wapentagium de Sadberge, eaque re&s;tituend. mercatoribus proprietar.</HI> Rot. Langley. N^o 27. 28th, 26th July, a'o 26th pont.&mdash;Ibid. Enq. p. 21. <HI>Vide commi&s;&s;ion per dict. epi&s;c. d'attornatio faciend. inde pro mercatoribus alienigenis.</HI>&mdash;Ibid. Enq.</P>
<P>Commi&s;&s;io T. Langley epi&s;c. 3d Feb. a'o 14 pont. &s;ui, 7&deg; Hen V. 1420. Radulpho d'Eure chivalier, Ri|chardo d' Norton, Jacobo Strangeway, Thomae Fulthorpe, Chri&s;tophero Boynton, Willielmo Chancel|lour, Roberto Strangeways, and Johanne Ai&s;laby, ad inquirend. &s;uper de&s;ect. aquar. &s;ecund. &s;tatut. et commune pa&s;&s;agium navium et batellorum in magnis ripariis, &amp;c. Salvis epi&s;c. omnibus amerciamentis. Rot. Langley B. N^o 48. 1420.&mdash;Ibid. Enq. p. 27.</P>
<P>The other commi&s;&s;ions of the like nature. Rot. E. N^o 41. 19 pont. Ibid. N^o 3. 24 pont. Rot. C. N^o 63. 31 pont.&mdash;Ibid.</P>
<P>Three commi&s;&s;ions per Langley epi&s;c. ad inquiread. &s;uper de&s;ect. pi&s;cium aquaram, i. e. d' &s;almonibus non capiend. in tempore juxta &s;tatut. de We&s;tm. 2 et 3.&mdash;Ibid. Enq. p. 29.</P>
<P>In the account of Sir Wm Claxtons knight, &s;heriff and e&s;cheator, 1416.&mdash;Wreccum maris. Et de pre|$cio unius corde vocat cable invent. apud Sheles provenient. de wrecco maris hoc anno 11&deg;.</P>
<P>Et de precio unius battelle cum toto apparatu et aliis rebus, &amp;c. et panno ru&s;ceto provenien. de wrecco maris anno preceden. 46 <ABBR><HI>s.</HI></ABBR> 8 <ABBR><HI>d.</HI></ABBR></P>
<P>In the account of Robert Eure &s;heriff and e&s;cheator, a'o 142&deg;.&mdash;Wreccum maris. Nil hoc anno preter unam navem rem. apud Hartlepool in cu&s;tod. Joh'es King.</P>
