<P>Item, for the overplus of the golde that went to the twoo cro&s;&s;es <HI>(carried before him in proce&s;&s;ion)</HI> for my lordis grace made of fine golde, oone garni&s;hed with &s;tone and perle poi&s;s. <HI>x</HI> ounces, for every ounce chaunge of the golde betwene corone gole and fine golde <HI>iiij</HI> <ABBR>s.</ABBR> <HI>iiij</HI> <ABBR>d.</ABBR> and for every ounce makyng of the <HI>x</HI> ounces <HI>vi</HI> <ABBR>s.</ABBR> <HI>viij</HI> <ABBR>d.</ABBR>&mdash;<HI>v</HI> <ABBR>l.</ABBR></P>
<P><HI>Page 288.</HI> Item, detiveryd to John Beynyarde of London gold&s;methe, at the reyque&s;te of mai&s;tar Go&s;twike my lordis &s;ervaunt, for the makyng of a harne&s;s for a moile <HI>(the cardinal's mule)</HI> oone hundred ounces &s;t$ the oz. <HI>iij</HI> <ABBR>s.</ABBR> <HI>iiij</HI> <ABBR>d.</ABBR>&mdash;<HI>xvj</HI> <ABBR>l.</ABBR> <HI>xiij</HI> <ABBR>s.</ABBR> <HI>iiij</HI> <ABBR>d.</ABBR></P>
