<P>In 1775, a mo&s;t elegant marble monument was erected to his memory in the chapel of Auckland, with the following in&s;cription:
<Q>RICHARDUS TREVOR Cujus Lector, contemplaris Imaginem, Filius natu Quartus <HI>THOMAE</HI> Domini <HI>TREVOR</HI> Bar: de <HI>BROMHAM</HI> &amp;ca. natus e&s;t <HI>LONDINI</HI> 30. Sept: A: D: 1707. &lazyS; Cur&s;um humaniorum Literarum In Schol&acirc; <HI>EPISCOPO-STORTFORD</HI> incohatum In Collegio <HI>REGINENSI OXON:</HI> Confecit. &lazyS; In Collegium <HI>OMNIUM ANIMARUM</HI> Socius co-optatus A: D: 1727. &lazyS; In &s;acro-&s;anctos Ordines initiatus A: D: 1731. Parochiae de <HI>HOUGHTON</HI> cum <HI>WITTON</HI> in Com: <HI>HUNT:</HI> Curam &s;u&s;cepit A: D: 1732; Su&s;ceptaeq; per xii: annos Vigilanter, ac liberaliter incubuit. &lazyS; <HI>GEORGIUM</HI> Secundum Ad <HI>HANOVERIAM</HI> a Sacris comitatus A: D: 1735. Eodem anno Canonicus <HI>AeDIS CHRISTI, OX:</HI> Regio ju&s;&s;u a&s;criptus e&s;t. &lazyS; Epi&s;copus <HI>MENEVIAe</HI> con&s;ecratus e&s;t A: D: 1744 Ibidemq; munere Pa&s;torali per octennium Perfideliter functus, Deniq; in hanc <HI>DIOCESIN,</HI> Quam digni&s;&s;im&egrave; admini&s;travit, Ampli&s;&s;im&egrave; exornavit, Sibiq; arcti&s;&s;im&egrave; devinxit, Tran&s;latus e&s;t A: D: 1752. &lazyS; Diem &s;upremum E&acirc;dem, qu&acirc; vixerat, Aequanimitate, Obiit <HI>LONDINI</HI> 9. Junii A: D: 1771; Ac in Aede Parochiali, Quam &s;uis &s;umptibus extruxerat Apud <HI>GLYND</HI> in Com: <HI>SUSSEX;</HI> Sepultus jacet. &lazyS; Nulli non flebilis occidit; Nulli flebilior quam &s;uis Haeredibus, Quorum pietas hoc Cenotaphium B: M: P: C: &lazyS;</Q></P>
<PB N="589" REF="651">
<P>The See was filled on the 8th of July, 1771, by the tran&s;lation of JOHN EGERTON, D.C.L. from the bi&s;hopric of Litchfield: His <HI>Cong&eacute; d'Elire</HI> arrived at Durham on the 27th of June: He did homage and received re&s;titution of the temporalties on the 1&s;t of Augu&s;t; was enthroned by his proxy, Dr Samuel Dickens, on the 2d of Augu&s;t; and in per&s;on on the 3d of September following.</P>
<P>The revenues of this See cannot be critically &s;hewn to the reader, as the offi|cers in the &s;everal departments are not at liberty to exhibit to the public the amount of their re&s;pective receipts; and, indeed, it would be extending the eye of curio&s;ity too far, to &s;earch into &s;ecrets which could give &s;o little gratification. What is already made public, and commonly known to tho&s;e re&s;ident in the county, will be given in an appendix to the &s;econd volume, with many other curious particulars.</P>
