<P>The copyholds of all the bi&s;hop's manors are e&s;tates of inheritance, and de&s;cend|able in fee. A certain &s;mall &s;ine, called demi&s;e money, as marked on the margin of every &s;urrender, is paid upon purcha&s;e, admittance of the heir, mortgagee, or other per&s;on, and cannot be enhanced at the will of the lord.&mdash;If any per&s;on pur|cha&s;es a copyhold, and takes the &s;urrender ab&s;olute to him&s;elf, his heirs, and &s;e|quels, in &s;uch ca&s;e he cannot devi&s;e the &s;ame by will, unle&s;s he previou&s;ly pa&s;s a &s;urrender to a tru&s;tee to the u&s;e thereof; nor can the widow be entitled to her frank-bank <HI>durante viduitate et ca&s;titate,</HI> unle&s;s her hu&s;band dies &s;ei&s;ed, and the legal e&s;tate not ve&s;ted in a tru&s;tee.</P>
<P>The bi&s;hop is entitled to work or demi&s;e by lea&s;e all the mines; he is al&s;o en|titled to all wood, which the copyholder cannot cut (unle&s;s for nece&s;&s;ary repairs) without licence and compo&s;ition fir&s;t made with the bi&s;hop.</P>
<P>In Gate&s;head and Whickham manors, the &s;urrenders mu&s;t be pre&s;ented to the homage, or they are not legal; but in all the other manors, they are pa&s;&s;ed before the &s;teward or his deputies.</P>
